sub_title: Postdoctoral Researcher at TNW/QN | TU Delft
summary: My research focuses on molecular and biomolecular charge and energy transport (in part on electron transfer (ET) mechanisms in molecules and molecular junctions). One of the main objectives of my research was to develop a physical understanding of how to control ET through small. Part of my research activity was in the field of molecular electronics and molecular junctions, in the sense that I explained current-voltage and current-temperature behaviors in ET-protein molecular junction experiments using various phenomenological models that describe specific transfer mechanisms. Also, I proposed novel junction experiments for observing and controlling the Marcus inverted regime in molecular junctions. Recently, I also finished work on exciton transport and singlet fission mechanisms in molecules. This work involves extensive analytical work, code writing and ab-initio quantum chemistry computations for the analysis of excited states. I am currently studying bacterial species that have been found to produce conductive structures, specifically Desulfobubaceae family wires, also known as cable bacteria. I develop theoretical models of electron transport (ETp) in metal cable bacterium filament-metal junction, based on coherent tunneling and incoherent hopping formalisms, that can describe conductance / current experiments in such microbial wires.
